WEBVTT

00:04.317 --> 00:12.346
Okay, this is Ron Shorn interviewing Heiss 
Spinrad at Heiss Home in Moraga, California on

00:04.317 --> 00:12.346
June 9th, 1993. Heida, just for the record, what's 
your full name? Heiren Spinrad. How do you spell

00:19.235 --> 00:20.075
that? H-Y-R-O-N-S-P-I-N-R-A-D.

00:25.782 --> 00:26.463
When were you born? Long ago. What date? February 
17th, 1934. And where were you born? New York. What

00:34.574 --> 00:35.335
part of New York? Bad part. Brooklyn? Actually, I 
think I was born in New York City, but I lived in

00:38.137 --> 00:41.741
Brooklyn after the first week. How did you get 
interested in astronomy? My grandmother was

00:45.845 --> 00:53.472
interested in a lot of intellectual things, 
family not having an extraordinarily

00:45.845 --> 00:53.472
intellectual background. I'm not sure where that 
started. But in any case, she brought several

00:55.434 --> 01:03.822
books home when I was, gosh, I don't know, between 
five and seven years of age. and I was interested in

01:04.628 --> 01:06.951
looking at the sky. When I was eight years old, 
during World War II, New York became blacked out,

01:07.552 --> 01:17.464
and therefore the sky got dark. So you could 
actually see the stars in the Milky Way, and

01:17.484 --> 01:21.469
everything that was supposed to be there was 
there. That was fairly inspiring to a young kid. So

01:26.054 --> 01:34.585
I think it was my grandmother's influence and the 
fact that you could see the sky and wonder about it

01:26.054 --> 01:34.585
that got me started, and then I got small telescope 
of relatively low quality that was adequate to see

01:35.543 --> 01:49.735
a few double stars and perhaps maybe barely the 
phases of Venus, and that helped a lot too. That was

01:49.815 --> 01:56.221
from some kind of pawn shop, I think. Did this 
interest in astronomy carry through high school?

01:59.123 --> 02:00.865
No, not vividly. In high school, I sort of got away 
from that and was more interested in in sports, and

02:05.429 --> 02:13.740
I still did okay in physics and chemistry and 
mathematics, but I didn't really have my heart in

02:05.429 --> 02:13.740
it. On the other hand, I didn't know what else to do 
when I went to start my undergraduate education at

02:14.201 --> 02:22.231
Berkeley, so I decided I would be an astronomer 
unless something better came along. How come

02:22.552 --> 02:25.976
Berkeley if you were born in New York City? Yes, 
good point. My family and I moved to California in

02:27.499 --> 02:33.867
1946 when I was 12 years old, in junior high school. 
So I did my junior high school and high school

02:36.162 --> 02:41.209
curriculum in San Francisco. Berkeley was 
nearby, in those days very inexpensive, and I

02:41.649 --> 02:54.827
could live there and not break the bank, which was 
relatively thin. So were you an astronomy major?

02:57.891 --> 03:00.274
Yeah, I was an astronomy major initially by 
default. Then after I took a class With Struve, I

03:02.669 --> 03:05.032
knew I really liked it. I don't know if he had a 
reputation of being a good teacher, but he was

03:06.535 --> 03:11.802
inspirational, whether he knew it or not. When did 
you get your bachelor's degree? Bachelor's

03:14.286 --> 03:16.229
degree was in 55. And then you went to grad school? 
No, I was in the Army for two years in between, in the

03:19.573 --> 03:31.731
Philippines, Marianas, Carolinas, and western 
U.S., measuring stellar occultations under John

03:19.573 --> 03:31.731
O'Keefe's project, which was to find the location 
of everything between the West Coast and China for

03:32.285 --> 03:36.692
unpeaceful reasons. Middle of the Cold War, of 
course.

03:43.061 --> 03:44.002
What was your thesis on? My thesis was the stellar 
content of nearby bright galaxies. I did that with

03:48.709 --> 03:51.273
Whitford and Mayall, predominantly. Did you pick 
that, or did they pick it for you? I picked it,

03:53.536 --> 04:02.089
actually, which was perhaps slightly unusual, 
and that made it a little bit hard to find the

03:53.536 --> 04:02.089
appropriate advisor, but it turned out that those 
two men Male and Woodford actually were perfect

04:02.305 --> 04:06.771
for this, and I learned a lot from them. Why did you 
pick that topic? Why were you interested in it?

04:10.255 --> 04:17.905
I've always been interested in stellar spectra, 
and the stellar content of galaxies, I thought,

04:10.255 --> 04:17.905
could be attacked in that way. And Morgan and Male 
had just come out with a paper doing a little bit of

04:17.945 --> 04:23.052
that in a very qualitative way. So it was somewhat 
of an outgrowth of the interest in stars and the

04:23.893 --> 04:31.603
timeliness of it and the availability of... 
relatively modest, or now we would say very

04:31.904 --> 04:36.070
modest, equipment on medium-sized telescopes. 
Which was like the Crosley, 36 inches. 0.9 meter,

04:38.633 --> 04:40.075
yeah, 36 inch. I used both 36 inches at Lick, 
actually, the Crosley more than the refractor.

04:45.042 --> 04:46.304
When did you get your PhD? PhD was in 61. Okay, and 
where did you go from there? Right to JPL. How come?

04:52.813 --> 04:53.774
Well, that was strange. Yeah, yeah, I know. Sagan 
had come to Berkeley in 60, I guess, as a Miller...

05:00.592 --> 05:03.418
fellow after his PhD from Chicago. And he was the 
first person around Berkeley to talk about

05:04.520 --> 05:19.292
planets in what then seemed a modern way, 
exploring them by spacecraft, exploring them in

05:04.520 --> 05:19.292
other ways, and doing more than just a few poorish 
review articles of the previous generation would

05:20.217 --> 05:25.522
suggest. Certainly Berkeley at the time was not a 
hotbed of planetary astronomy. There was some

05:30.447 --> 05:33.609
celestial mechanics, of course, going on. How did 
you pick JPL, or did they come around? I

05:37.893 --> 05:39.655
interviewed a bunch of places. I wanted to stay in 
California if possible for family reasons

05:39.675 --> 05:47.102
predominantly, and I checked out A couple places. 
There were industrial places that were looking

05:48.847 --> 05:55.381
for astronomers then, too, although those jobs 
later turned out to be kind of ephemeral. What,

05:55.501 --> 05:57.786
like North American aviation? Aeroneutronics 
from Ford.

06:02.095 --> 06:07.707
Lockheed, I think, were in general not so much the 
time I was actually looking around. A couple other

06:08.429 --> 06:11.612
places whose names I've gracefully forgotten. 
Were those places funded by the Air Force or by NASA

06:11.972 --> 06:17.498
or what? I'm not really sure. I never dug into it 
that deeply. Probably anything they could come up

06:20.260 --> 06:22.142
with. So probably all those. Anyway, JPL was 
another one on the list, and I went down there and

06:23.403 --> 06:28.488
checked out Caltech. Greenstein had a postdoc 
available, and JPL did them sort of both in the same

06:28.929 --> 06:34.874
week. And... Of course, Greenstein would have 
been interested in me working on stars with his

06:36.425 --> 06:41.471
abundance program. And, of course, JPL would have 
been, at that time, happy to get an astronomer. Who

06:47.639 --> 06:50.082
got the Greenstein thing? I don't remember. 
Probably Sargent. Or Bob O'Dell or something.

06:54.628 --> 06:57.531
O'Dell did get something down there, but I think 
that was at Carnegie, actually. It was about the

06:57.732 --> 06:59.534
same time, within a few months. The O'Dells and... 
Our family actually were in the same apartment

07:03.188 --> 07:09.875
complex, and the two wives met by accident over a 
clothesline. It's a funny story in itself. Okay,

07:12.137 --> 07:15.041
you arrived at JPL. Were you their first PhD 
astronomer? Yeah, I think so. Of course, Ray

07:19.285 --> 07:21.527
Newbern had been there for some time before. Who 
was your boss? Was Luke Kaplan the boss? Not yet.

07:26.272 --> 07:32.419
No, there was another guy who really didn't have a 
technical background, who was the de facto

07:26.272 --> 07:32.419
section boss, but in practice... Ray was just 
about that without the stature or pay. And when you

07:39.136 --> 07:44.946
got there and looked around, what did you think of 
the place? I mean, there weren't any big

07:45.026 --> 07:46.669
telescopes or anything. No, there weren't any big 
telescopes, which created a problem that we'll

07:46.689 --> 07:50.095
talk about shortly. That was, of course, a very 
severe problem. But initially, I wasn't panicked

07:52.239 --> 07:54.083
about that. The main job I was assigned to do at 
first supposedly half time, but I had no idea what

07:58.032 --> 08:15.955
fraction of time would be, was to coordinate an 
instrument designed by Dr. Charles Barth, who

07:58.032 --> 08:15.955
then was at JPL, a UV spectrometer, I think, to get 
ultraviolet spectra of planets from spacecraft.

08:17.577 --> 08:21.021
I'm not positive if the first one was a Mariner 
Venus. Probably was, but I'm not positive of that

08:21.682 --> 08:23.905
any longer. In any case, so I was supposed to 
coordinate Barth and his engineers and the rest of

08:24.307 --> 08:50.112
the project, which seemed like a strange role for a 
fresh PhD who didn't know ultraviolet from the

08:24.307 --> 08:50.112
bomber limit and certainly had no previous 
experience dealing with interesting and

08:24.307 --> 08:50.112
creative and, to be brutally frank about it, quite 
egotistical personalities. But you learn when

08:50.817 --> 08:52.259
you do these things. And actually, that turned out 
to be mildly interesting and took much less of my

08:52.299 --> 08:58.305
time than I thought it would. So I did actually have 
time to initiate research if I wanted to. And I did a

09:02.610 --> 09:08.376
little bit of continued work on galaxies, but I 
figured I wasn't being paid by JPL to do that. So I

09:08.396 --> 09:20.790
figured I would look into the possibilities in 
planetary astronomy in areas that I had a little

09:08.396 --> 09:20.790
bit of previous knowledge, that is spectroscopy 
of the planets, and was annoyed to find that there

09:21.310 --> 09:23.332
wasn't any modern data. There certainly was no 
prospect of more coming in, at least nothing that I

09:24.073 --> 09:29.199
would have any involvement in. And therefore, I 
turned to the old historical data, which

09:29.859 --> 09:40.752
astronomers generally keep forever, especially 
in the days where photography was the prime method

09:29.859 --> 09:40.752
of recording information. It's actually easier 
to document photographic plate files than it is to

09:45.273 --> 09:51.342
get people's CCD images in 1993, but that's 
getting far afield. So in any case, I sort of fell

09:51.623 --> 10:01.217
upon the Mount Wilson plate files, and that turned 
out to be an interesting intro to planetary

09:51.623 --> 10:01.217
astronomy. These were mainly photographic 
spectra taken by Dunham and associates in the late

10:01.258 --> 10:08.749
30s, and through World War II at a relatively low 
pace. At which telescope? Ah, sorry. Mostly at the

10:14.113 --> 10:15.915
100-inch telescope. This is pre-200-inch, and 
the 200-inch spectrograph wasn't particularly

10:15.935 --> 10:20.340
better than the 100-inch anyway. So it was 
100-inch Coudet spectra, by and large, although

10:20.881 --> 10:27.168
there were other types of spectra. But those were 
the ones that had the most recorded information

10:27.188 --> 10:34.737
and seemed to be amenable to some kind of new 
quantitative or semi-quantitative analysis.

10:41.075 --> 10:44.899
And they were done when the seeing was too poor to do 
stellar astronomy? I'm not sure if it was

10:44.960 --> 10:47.483
completely that. I mean, Dunham actually was a 
staff member, so it wasn't, I don't believe, I

10:47.503 --> 10:59.117
don't know the politics back that far precisely, 
but my guess is that he probably didn't have to beg

10:47.503 --> 10:59.117
as hard as an outsider would. But they were 
definitely not done during prime hours. Some of

11:03.901 --> 11:05.166
them were done in the daytime. I think a lot of them 
were done after the sun was down, or else there

11:05.206 --> 11:09.804
would have been more scattered light on them. What 
did you get out of them? Well, I got some things

11:11.234 --> 11:16.742
which later turned out not to be quite correct, but 
nevertheless, at the time, they seemed

11:11.234 --> 11:16.742
interesting. I was trying to measure the physical 
parameters of the atmosphere of Venus from a study

11:16.782 --> 11:33.867
of the carbon dioxide bands in the near-infrared, 
which at high dispersion can give you information

11:16.782 --> 11:33.867
on the rotational temperature of the CO2 gas, 
which ought to be in a high-density atmosphere

11:16.782 --> 11:33.867
equal to the kinetic temperature of the 
atmosphere, whatever optical depth is

11:34.488 --> 11:37.311
appropriate. That's a little tricky in a cloudy 
atmosphere, but neglecting that complication,

11:37.431 --> 11:52.226
it sounded like a good idea to look at whether Venus 
was hot or cold a little bit deeper in the

11:37.431 --> 11:52.226
atmosphere than infrared or such measures could 
at the time do easily. And secondarily, if you

11:52.666 --> 12:01.875
measure the line widths carefully and if there are 
no other broadening mechanisms, you can get some

11:52.666 --> 12:01.875
idea of the pressure also at the mean optical 
depth. Now the last part I think was done with some

12:04.407 --> 12:07.411
naivete, as you'll look back on it 30 years. But of 
course, when you started, it was better than

12:07.431 --> 12:12.097
anything else in the field. Definitely. Yes. I 
asked Bill Sinton about the Sinton band, so I've

12:15.461 --> 12:21.048
got to ask High Spinrad about the effect Spinrad. 
Oh, the Jovian line tilt. Yes. I still haven't

12:23.090 --> 12:24.912
quite figured that one out. Let me give a little 
preface on that. Why does one have to get your name

12:28.197 --> 12:32.642
attached to all things both good and bad? In any 
case, the ammonia and methane lines in the

12:33.398 --> 12:51.183
spectrum of Jupiter when the spectrograph slit is 
placed along the equator to get the rotational

12:33.398 --> 12:51.183
velocity turn out to be tilted approximately half 
as much as the reflected lines from the solar

12:33.398 --> 12:51.183
spectrum. The factor of two comes in basically 
just a moving mirror and our aspect on Earth in the

12:51.223 --> 12:58.073
simplest of geometries when the Sun, Earth, and 
the outer planet, like Jupiter, are lined up, give

12:58.525 --> 13:07.715
you just precisely a factor of two, because one of 
the components is Sun, Jupiter, and the other,

12:58.525 --> 13:07.715
Jupiter, Earth. And in the case of the methane and 
ammonia bands, which are physically from the

13:08.235 --> 13:13.321
Jovian atmosphere, you only get one of those. So 
that tilt should be a factor of two less. And on some

13:15.964 --> 13:18.547
spectra that Munch had obtained, and perhaps... 
This is Guido Munch. Guido Munch, yes, professor

13:19.387 --> 13:23.672
of astronomy at Caltech at the time. It looked like 
the tilts were rather less than that, as if the

13:24.732 --> 13:33.012
ammonia wasn't co-rotating with the atmospheric 
velocity. Trouble is, the tilt was so different

13:33.052 --> 13:39.467
from a half that the velocity difference you 
predict turns out to probably be supersonic,

13:33.052 --> 13:39.467
which was a bit weird, but as an empiricist, I was 
quite willing to accept the observations. I'm not

13:46.053 --> 14:06.223
quite sure what's happened, but every time 
anybody else, including me, in future years tried

13:46.053 --> 14:06.223
to reproduce the observations, which again were 
fairly old at the time, the strange deviation from

13:46.053 --> 14:06.223
half the expected tilt did not reproduce. So I've 
always assumed that there was some peculiarity in

14:08.050 --> 14:15.147
the way I measured the plates, but it doesn't 
really make complete sense. So I'm not 100% sure

14:15.167 --> 14:18.775
now what went wrong, but I'm pretty sure something 
did. I don't believe it's a physical effect. It

14:21.702 --> 14:25.772
drew a lot of attention, again, to planetary 
astronomy, but not necessarily for the best of

14:21.702 --> 14:25.772
reasons. Did you try and get Telescope Time to do 
New Spectrum? Yeah, sure. And that was a long and

14:30.299 --> 14:36.511
cluttered story, which basically was mostly 
unsuccessful. Well, it was obvious that one could

14:36.891 --> 14:43.423
do better by doing things yourself when you knew 
what the problem was going to be, or in many cases,

14:43.403 --> 14:44.906
with improved instrumentation. I mean, this is 
still the era of photography, but, for example, in

14:45.527 --> 14:53.661
near-infrared spectroscopy, fore-end plates 
had replaced one-ends, and those have much higher

14:45.527 --> 14:53.661
acuity. And generally, just the idea of doing 
something yourself when you know what was

14:54.422 --> 15:01.615
happening at the telescope is better than going 
down to some archaic file and not knowing all

15:02.000 --> 15:05.345
circumstances except what's written on the 
envelope of the plate. So at first, I made casual

15:06.587 --> 15:20.667
approaches to various observers and observatory 
directors at Mount Wilson, at McDonald, back at

15:06.587 --> 15:20.667
Lick, old stomping grounds. And these were not 
greeted generally with much enthusiasm for

15:21.102 --> 15:26.828
perhaps several reasons. I'm not positive which 
ones were the most important. Planetary

15:30.711 --> 15:35.836
astronomy still was not considered part of 
mainstream astronomy. And I think this was

15:35.856 --> 15:45.986
probably the largest factor in the sense that 
directors and other people that ran

15:35.856 --> 15:45.986
observatories were worried perhaps about 
wasting valuable observing time. In other words,

15:46.921 --> 15:49.064
real astronomers look down on planets. Yeah, for 
better or for worse, that was the case at the very

15:49.084 --> 15:53.329
beginning of the space age. I mean, obviously it 
evolved, but initially that was true. Were you

15:56.854 --> 16:00.178
ever told you made your choice between money and 
telescope time? Not in writing. But orally? Yeah.

16:03.422 --> 16:04.123
Yeah, okay. And we're slightly more diplomatic 
than that. Yeah, I won't, in fact, mention the

16:07.788 --> 16:14.457
person that said it the most bluntly, because it's 
a guy you don't even know. Okay. But, yeah, I was

16:16.030 --> 16:18.954
told that, and it was painful. JPL, of course, for 
those uninitiated, paid a lot more than a

16:19.535 --> 16:36.417
low-level academic job, starting salaries at JPL 
were twice that of a postdoc and probably, I'm just

16:19.535 --> 16:36.417
guessing, 40% or 50% higher than an assistant 
professor would have been at the same time. So for a

16:36.637 --> 16:39.441
fresh Ph.D., it was a lot of money. Now, 
technically, JPL was a part of Caltech. Yes. But

16:45.297 --> 16:47.159
practically, it was not. Is that correct? Yes. 
There was a vast chasm that separated the

16:48.340 --> 16:58.592
stature, so to speak, of JPL scientists with 
Caltech science. In some cases, that was at least

16:58.612 --> 17:01.415
true in some areas. That wasn't true in every 
endeavor. I think the people that did radio and

17:04.138 --> 17:13.129
radar astronomy were considered colleagues of 
equal footing, perhaps. But in any case, Yes,

17:15.008 --> 17:27.849
Caltech was not a cooperative partner in any sense 
of the word, with one major exception, and that was

17:15.008 --> 17:27.849
the influence of Guido Munch, professor of 
astronomy at Caltech. Guido, for his own personal

17:27.869 --> 17:37.164
interests, was interested in a variety of topics, 
very, very broad person, and one of those was

17:27.869 --> 17:37.164
planetary astronomy. So, on his own, he was doing a 
fair amount of observing of planets, but even more

17:39.646 --> 17:46.493
importantly, from my own personal viewpoint, he 
was around as a pseudo-mentor. I mean, he's the

17:46.513 --> 17:50.937
last person on Earth that would probably like to be 
accused of being a good teacher. But in any case,

17:51.778 --> 17:56.342
like it or not, he was in his own strange way. You 
were reduced to looking for water vapor on planets

17:58.644 --> 18:03.949
at Victoria, British Columbia, were you not? 
Excellent choice, wouldn't you think? All right,

18:06.781 --> 18:08.363
so that's a long story. Any case, let me make it 
quite abbreviated. Water on Mars is a long, long

18:11.085 --> 18:18.493
story, which, in fact, you have documented well.

18:21.396 --> 18:28.923
My own interest in that came, again, just from 
reading the review papers by Richardson, Dunham,

18:21.396 --> 18:28.923
and other folks. And then the first attempts to try 
to observe water from balloon altitudes by, I

18:29.584 --> 18:36.771
think, Dollfuss, actually, was the first, 
perhaps, to be successful. And people had thought

18:37.105 --> 18:39.147
about this before. And there have been attempts at 
Lowell Observatory also. The trick, of course, is

18:42.671 --> 18:50.360
to have a dry site on Earth and or a Doppler shift to 
move out the telluric lines from the Martian ones.

18:50.400 --> 19:01.392
The Mars lines, obviously, were going to be very 
weak since we know there's not very much water on

18:50.400 --> 19:01.392
Mars if you spread out the polar caps, assuming 
that they're half water or something like that.

19:01.412 --> 19:05.577
You don't get a lot of water in the atmosphere at the 
temperatures relevant to Mars. So I tried to get

19:06.839 --> 19:12.869
time at Mount Wilson, and that would have required 
using the 100-inch. The snow telescope, which I

19:13.650 --> 19:21.664
did use for Venus, was inadequate even for Venus, 
unfortunately. It was OK for getting a spectrum of

19:21.884 --> 19:23.687
the sun, however. I learned a little bit by using 
it. But that was as much as the observatory

19:25.931 --> 19:32.442
committee and Director Bowen was willing to give 
to me. I asked other places at Lick. I got a polite

19:36.847 --> 20:01.585
reply from Director Albert Whitford, who 
remarked that they had just gotten their big

19:36.847 --> 20:01.585
telescope, the three-meter, what's called the 
Shane, but now the Shane, a three-meter

19:36.847 --> 20:01.585
telescope, had just gone on the air there, and they 
had been second-rate citizens to the Mount Wilson

19:36.847 --> 20:01.585
Palomar folks for so long that they weren't 
anxious to give time away to, quotes Caltech,

20:02.223 --> 20:05.908
quote, unquote, and Whitford remarked that I 
should, you know, try here. And meaning at

20:06.689 --> 20:07.651
Caltech. Yeah, yeah, right, which, you know, is a 
logical thing to say. He wasn't trying to be

20:09.894 --> 20:11.717
particularly mean about it. I was very defensive. 
Well, nevertheless, nothing came of that. So I

20:16.223 --> 20:22.172
tried also, I think, that early at McDonald's, but 
I'm not positive it was really at that time. Was

20:22.192 --> 20:23.935
this before Harlan took over? Oh, yes. When Kuiper 
was still director. I think, actually, I had to do

20:26.859 --> 20:29.082
it through the University of Chicago. Maybe I 
didn't, but I did. In any case, it was definitely

20:30.893 --> 20:32.736
before Harlan Smith. Well, let's continue on that 
now. So I ended up then finding out, I don't

20:35.401 --> 20:46.381
remember who told me, that they had a new 40-inch 
telescope, 48-inch telescope at Victoria,

20:35.401 --> 20:46.381
British Columbia, which is, of course, an insane 
place to go looking for water. You find it very

20:47.142 --> 20:48.525
locally. Yes, you can hardly avoid it. But even on a 
clear night, it's not particularly dry. It's

20:52.612 --> 20:53.433
about as wet a side as you can. And it's far north, 
too. It's far north. The elevation is about 100

20:55.784 --> 20:57.346
meters. It's a real wet place. On the other hand, 
they've got a good telescope and a nice modern

20:59.450 --> 21:03.576
spectrograph that had been built by Harvey 
Richardson. So I got some time there with no more

21:04.277 --> 21:12.369
difficulty than suggesting a collaboration with 
Richardson, who had a mild interest in planetary

21:04.277 --> 21:12.369
work. And I don't know why they gave me time, but 
they did. I think it was, you know, something like a

21:19.088 --> 21:27.444
couple weeks a year, which was a heck of a lot for 
their second most powerful telescope and

21:19.088 --> 21:27.444
certainly their modern telescope. So we got some 
observations despite the usual difficulties

21:28.546 --> 21:32.974
with weather up there. Not good enough to find 
water on Mars or Venus, but we got some good enough

21:33.495 --> 21:42.632
spectra to be interesting and to whet everybody's 
appetite and to show that modern spectra, after we

21:33.495 --> 21:42.632
learned how to, you know, walk and climb a bit 
